4. How do you create reusable modules? 
I create reusable Terraform modules by grouping related resources into logical components such as VPC, IAM, ECS, or logging. For example, a VPC module would contain subnets, route tables, NAT gateways, and security-related networking resources.
Each module is structured with main.tf for resources, variables.tf for configurable inputs, and outputs.tf for values consumed by other modules. I keep inputs clean and parameterized to avoid hardcoding, and expose only the outputs that are needed.
I also version modules, document usage, and validate them through CI pipelines or tests before release. Root modules then consume these shared modules with environment-specific values.
This approach reduces code duplication, improves consistency, and makes infrastructure easier to maintain at scale.  Questions -  I also version modules, document usage, and validate them through CI pipelines or tests before release.  “We version our Terraform modules using semantic versioning (major, minor, patch). After changes are merged, we create a Git tag (e.g. v1.2.0) to mark the release. This can be done either via the GitHub Releases UI or through Git commands. The tagged version is then referenced in Terraform so consumers can use stable, versioned modules.”
