6. How do you handle drift detection? 
Terraform drift occurs when the actual infrastructure differs from Terraform’s expected state based on the configuration and state file, usually due to manual changes outside Terraform.
I detect drift primarily by running terraform plan, either manually or through scheduled CI/CD jobs, which highlights unexpected changes.
Once detected, I first verify whether the live infrastructure was intentionally changed or whether it is unauthorized/untracked. If the infrastructure should match the Terraform code, I remediate by applying Terraform. If the manual change was valid, I update the Terraform configuration so the code becomes the source of truth.
To reduce future drift, I restrict direct console changes through IAM controls and encourage all infrastructure changes through reviewed Terraform pipelines.
