8. How do workspaces differ from separate state files?  
Terraform workspaces create separate state files within the same backend, so environments like dev, test, and prod can use the same codebase while maintaining separate state. This is useful for lightweight environment separation.
However, workspaces typically still share the same backend configuration, repository, and operational context, so isolation is more logical than physical.
Separate state files or separate backends use dedicated S3 keys, buckets, or even separate AWS accounts for each environment. That provides stronger access control, reduced blast radius, and better governance—especially for production environments.
In enterprise setups, I usually see workspaces as suitable for simpler use cases, while separate backends/accounts are preferred for critical production workloads.  terraform init -backend-config=dev.backend terraform init -backend-config=prod.backend
   
